timeline.bodyText:
@g4s8 maybe it's better to rewrite it using ItemAt?
return new IoChecked<>(
    () -> new ItemAt<>(
        idx,
        new Split(
            this.line,
            "\\s"
        )
    ).value().asString()
).value();

Or even simpler if we're able to change exception in signature to just Exception:
new ItemAt<>(
    idx,
    new Split(
        this.line,
        "\\s"
    )
).value().asString();

Another option is to change method signature to private Text part(final int idx) throws IOException. That'll give us opportunity to write even more concise:
new IoChecked<>(
    new ItemAt<>(
        idx,
        new Split(
            this.line,
            "\\s"
        )
    )
).value();

replies.bodyText:
@iakunin it looks to verbose for me, see:
return new IoChecked<>(
    () -> new ItemAt<>(idx, new Split(this.line, "\\s")).value().asString()
).value();
vs:
return new IoChecked<>(this.line::asString).value().split("\\s")[idx];
The problem of Cactoos version here is verbose exception handling for code which can't throw checked exceptions.
